\par
"Dr. Reggis," Claire said sympathetically. "Becky is in worse condition today than she was yesterday, and yesterday she was in no condition to be transferred. But plasmaphoresis is not totally out of the question. There's still hope they could give the green light. We'll just have to wait."\par
\par
"Wait and do nothing," Kim said with a scowl.\par
\par
"That's not true," Claire said hotly. Then she caught herself and sighed; talking with Kim was a chore she did not relish. "We're supporting her every way possible."\par
\par
"Meaning you're sitting on your hands and treating complications," Kim spat.\par
\par
Claire stood up and looked at Tracy and Kathleen. "I think it's time for me to see the rest of my inpatients. But I'll be available if needed: just page me."\par
\par
Tracy nodded. Kathleen responded that she'd be doing the same thing in a few minutes. Claire left.\par
\par
Kim collapsed into the chair vacated by Claire and buried his head in his hands. He was struggling with a roller coaster of emotions: first anger and then sadness, then back to anger. Now sadness returned. He fought back tears. He knew he should be seeing his own inpatients, but for the moment he was incapable.\par
\par
"Why did your visit to the Onion Ring take so long?" Tracy asked. As irritated as she was by his behavior, she couldn't help but be concerned about him. He looked pitiful.\par
\par
"Actually, I was in jail," Kim admitted.\par
\par
"Jail!"\par
\par
"If you want me to tell you that you were right, you were right," Kim said. "I should have calmed down before I went."\par
\par
"Why were you in jail?" Tracy asked.\par
\par
"I lost my temper," Kim said. "I went there to find out about the possibility of tainted meat. The manager's self-righteous denial drove me up the wall."\par
\par
