Bartonville was less than forty minutes out of town. Kim cruised down its main street and then followed the directions he'd gotten from a service station at the freeway exit. He found Mercer Meats without a problem.\par
\par
It was a far bigger plant than he'd expected. The building was all white and modern-looking but otherwise nondescript. The grounds were immaculately landscaped with granite-lined drives and islands of trees in the parking area. The whole complex projected an aura of high profitability.\par
\par
Kim parked relatively near the front door in one of a half-dozen "visitor" spaces. He slid out from behind the wheel and started toward the entrance. As he walked, he reminded himself not to lose his temper. After the experience at the Onion Ring, he knew that if he did, it would only work against him.\par
\par
The reception area looked like it belonged at the entrance to an insurance company rather than a meat-packing concern. Plush wall-to-wall carpeting covered the floor, the furniture was richly upholstered, and there were framed prints on the walls. Only the subject matter of the prints gave a hint of the nature of the business: they were prints of various breeds of cattle.\par
\par
A matronly woman wearing a cordless headset sat at a circular desk in the center of the room.\par
\par
"May I help you?" she asked.\par
\par
"I hope so," Kim said. "What's the name of the president of Mercer Meats?"\par
\par
"That would be Mr. Everett Sorenson," the woman said.\par
\par
"Would you call Mr. Sorenson and tell him that Dr. Kim Reggis is here to see him?" Kim said.\par
\par
"Can I tell Mr. Sorenson what this is about?" the woman asked. She eyed Kim skeptically. His appearance was bordering on that of a homeless person.\par
\par
"Is it necessary?" Kim asked.\par
\par
"Mr. Sorenson is a very busy man," the woman said.\par
\par
"In that case," Kim said, "tell him it's about Mercer Meats selling contaminated hamburger patties to the Onion Ring restaurant chain."\par
\par
"Excuse me?" the woman said. She'd heard Kim, but couldn't quite believe it.\par
\par
