Kelly exhaled loudly and detached her microphone. In the background Marilyn's voice could be heard: "Thank you, Kelly, for that heartbreaking and disturbing story. Now on to other local news...\par
\par
Kelly activated the automatic garage door and then stepped out of her car as it began to shut. She slung her shoulder bag over her shoulder and climbed the three steps from the garage into the house.\par
\par
The house was quiet. She had expected to see Caroline sitting on the gingham couch watching her half hour of allotted television, but the TV was off and Caroline was nowhere in sight. All Kelly could hear was the faint clicking of a computer keyboard coming from the library.\par
\par
Kelly opened the refrigerator and poured herself some juice. Glass in hand, she passed through the dining room and poked her head into the library. Edgar was at the computer. Walking in, she gave him a peck on the cheek, which he accepted without taking his eyes off the monitor.\par
\par
"That was an interesting piece you did on Dr. Reggis," Edgar said. He double-clicked his mouse and looked up.\par
\par
"You think so?" Kelly said without a lot of enthusiasm. "Thanks."\par
\par
"A sad story for everyone involved," Edgar said.\par
\par
"To say the least." Kelly said. "A year ago he could have been a poster boy for American success. As a heart surgeon, he had it all: respect, a beautiful family, a big home, all the trappings."\par
\par
"But it was a house of cards," Edgar said.\par
\par
"Apparently," Kelly said. She sighed. "What's with Caroline? Did she get her homework done?"\par
\par
"Mostly." Edgar said. "But she wasn't feeling too good and wanted to go to bed."\par
\par
"What's the trouble?" Kelly asked. It was rare for Caroline to miss her TV.\par
\par
"Nothing overwhelming," Edgar assured her. "Just some stomach upset with cramps. She probably ate too much and too quickly. She insisted we stop at an Onion Ring restaurant after her skating practice, and the place was mobbed. I'm afraid her eyes were bigger than her stomach. She ordered two burgers, a shake, and a large fries."\par
\par
Kelly felt an uncomfortable stirring in the pit of her stomach.\par
\par
"Which Onion Ring?" Kelly asked hesitantly.\par
\par
"The one out on Prairie Highway," Edgar said.\par
\par
"Do you think Caroline is already asleep?" Kelly asked.\par
\par
"I wouldn't know for sure," Edgar said. "But she hasn't been up there very long."\par
\par
Kelly put down her juice. She left the room and climbed the stairs. Her face reflected her anxiety. She stopped to listen outside of Caroline's room. Once again, all she could hear was the clicking of the computer keyboard drifting up from downstairs.\par
\par
Quietly Kelly cracked the door. The room was dark.\par
\par
Opening the door further, she stepped inside and silently walked over to her daughter's bedside.\par
\par
Caroline was fast asleep. Her face looked particularly angelic. Her breathing was deep and regular.\par
\par
Kelly resisted the temptation to reach out and hug her daughter. Instead she just stood there in the semidarkness, thinking about how much she loved Caroline and how much Caroline meant to her. Such thoughts made her feel acutely vulnerable. Life was indeed a house of cards.\par
\par
Backing out of the room, Kelly closed the door and descended the stairs. She returned to the library, collected her juice glass, and sat down on the leather couch. She cleared her throat.\par
\par
Edgar looked over. Knowing Kelly as well as he did, he knew she wanted to talk. He switched off his computer.\par
\par
"What is it?" he asked.\par
\par
"It's the Dr. Reggis story," Kelly said. "I'm not satisfied with it. I said as much to the news director, but he overruled me, saying it was tabloid fodder not hard news and that I wasn't supposed to waste any more time on it. But I'm going to do it anyway."\par
\par
"Why do you feel this way?" Edgar asked.\par
\par
"There are some gnawing loose ends," Kelly said. "'The biggest one involves a USDA inspector by the name of Marsha Baldwin. When Kim Reggis stopped here on Sunday, he told me that he thought the woman had disappeared. He implied that foul play may have been involved?"\par
\par
"I assume you have been looking for her," Edgar said.\par
\par
"Sort of," Kelly admitted. "I really didn't take Kim Reggis too seriously. As I told you, I thought he'd gone over the edge after his daughter's death. I mean, he'd been acting bizarre and according to him the woman had only been missing for a few hours. Anyway I attributed his allegations to raving paranoia."\par
\par
"So you haven't found the woman," Edgar said.\par
\par
"No, I haven't," Kelly said. "Monday I made a few isolated calls, but I wasn't really into it. But today I called the USDA district office. When I asked about her, they insisted I talk to the district manager. Of course I didn't mind talking to the head honcho, but then he didn't give me any information. He just said that they hadn't seen her. After I hung up, I thought that it was curious that I had to speak to the head of the office to get that kind of information."\par
\par
"It is curious," Edgar admitted.\par
\par
"I called up later and asked specifically where she'd been assigned," Kelly said. "Guess where?"\par
\par
"I haven't a clue," Edgar said.\par
\par
"Mercer Meats," Kelly said.\par
\par
"Interesting," Edgar said. "So how are you going to go about investigating all this?"\par
\par
"I don't know yet," Kelly said. "Of course I'd love to find the doctor. Seems like I've always been chasing him."\par
\par
"Well, I've learned to respect your intuition," Edgar said. "So go for it."\par
\par
"One other thing," Kelly said. "Keep Caroline out of the Onion Ring restaurants, particularly the one on Prairie Highway."\par
\par
"How come?" Edgar asked. "She loves the food."\par
\par
"For the moment, let's just say it's my intuition."\par
\par
"You'll have to tell her yourself," Edgar said.\par
\par
"I don't have a problem with that," Kelly said.\par
\par
The door chimes surprised both of them. Kelly glanced at her watch. "Who's here ringing our bell at eight o'clock on a Tuesday?" she questioned.\par
\par
"Beats me," Edgar said, while getting to his feet. "Let me get it."\par
\par
"Be my guest," Kelly said.\par
\par
Kelly rubbed her temples as she gave more thought to Edgar's question about how she would look into this Reggis situation. Without the doctor, it wasn't going to be easy. She tried to remember everything Kim had said when he'd visited on Sunday.\par
\par
Out in the front hall she heard Edgar talking with someone and being told where to sign. A few minutes later, he returned. He was clutching a manila envelope, staring at the label.\par
\par
"You got a package," he said. He shook it. Something was moving around freely inside.\par
\par
"Who's it from?" Kelly asked. She didn't like getting mystery packages.\par
\par
"There's no return address," Edgar said. "Just the initials KR."\par
\par
"KR." Kelly repeated. "Kim Reggis?"\par
\par
Edgar shrugged. "I suppose it's possible."\par
\par
"Let me see it," Kelly said.\par
\par
Edgar handed her the package. She felt through the paper. "Well, it doesn't feel dangerous. It feels like a reel of something padded with paper."\par
\par
"Go ahead and open it," Edgar said.\par
\par
Kelly tore open the envelope and pulled out a bunch of official-looking forms and a recording tape. Attached to the top of the tape was a Post-it. On it was written: Kelly, You asked for documentation, and here it is. I'll be in touch. Kim Reggis.\par
\par
"These are all papers from Higgins and Hancock," Edgar said. "With attached descriptions."\par
\par
Kelly shook her head as she scanned the material. "I have a feeling my investigation just got off to a flying start."\par
